  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Awful after post Op experience&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Hayley&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;Came in as an NHS patient for gallbladder removal on 6.11.19 at 8.30am. Surgical staff including porter were amazing but experience on the ward afterwards left me with anxiety.  I was left in a room with no bell started vomiting vigorously filled a whole green bowl but and no one showed up.  I had to sit up abruptly and my wound bled (as it was only glued) and I wet the bed.  A lady finally came passed the door and ran to get help.  Nurse was only happy that I had  passed urine and I had to get up to change the bed she kept saying I could eat something when I felt better and then go home.  She gave me a drug intravenously to stop the vomiting.  By then thank goodness a friend showed up to help me about 40 minutes later I started throwing up again and my blood pressure got quite low, I wasn't quite sure what was happening.  Another nurse came and gave me a second drug, she injected the saline, dropped the needle picked it up wiped it off and stuck it back in to continue giving me the drug ( friend only revealed this to me a few days later) my friend ran to tell a lead nurse.  I was bought a sandwich and cup of tea then the nurse said I had to get dressed and call my husband to be collected.  I had thrown up over 3 bowls of a golden solution, don't think I should have been sent home.  I was given a GP release form but didn't see a GP.  I had to visit the dr two days later with anxiety and was put n beta blockers.  My wound took ages to heal.
&lt;/CommentText&gt;
